\title[Spectrality of Product Sets]{Spectrality of Product Sets with a Perturbed Interval Factor}

\author[A. Ramabadran]{Aditya Ramabadran}
\address{Department of Mathematics, University of California, Berkeley\\
970 Evans Hall\\
Berkeley, CA 94720, United States of America}
\email{aditya.ramabadran@berkeley.edu}

\author[J. van Vliet]{Johannes van Vliet}
\address{Department of Mathematics, University of Washington\\
Box 354350 C138 Padelford Hall\\
Seattle, WA 98195, United States of America}
\email{johov@uw.edu}

\date{\today}

\begin{abstract}
A set $\Omega \subset \mathbb{R}^d$ is said to be spectral if $L^2(\Omega)$ admits an orthogonal basis of exponentials. While the product of spectral sets is known to be spectral, the converse fails in general. In this paper, we prove the converse when one factor is a perturbation of an interval: if $m(E)=1$, $E \subset [0,3/2 - \epsilon]$, and $F \subset \R^m$ is bounded and measurable with positive measure, then $E \times F$ being spectral implies that both $E$ and $F$ are spectral. Since products of spectral sets are spectral, this gives the equivalence.
\end{abstract}

\subjclass[2020]{42C99}
\keywords{Fuglede's Conjecture, Weak Tiling, Nonharmonic Fourier Series}

\maketitle

\section{Introduction}
Suppose $\Omega \subset \R^d$ is a bounded set of positive measure. If for some countable set $\Lambda \subset \R^d$, $\{ \exp(2\pi i \langle\lambda,x\rangle ) \}_{\lambda \in \Lambda}$ is an orthogonal basis of $L^2(\Omega)$, we say that $\Omega$ is \textit{spectral} and $\Lambda$ is a \textit{spectrum} for $\Omega$. Most notably, Fuglede conjectured that a set $\Omega$ is spectral if and only if it can tile the space $\R^d$ by translations \cite{Fug74}. Although counterexamples were found in dimensions $d \ge 3$ \cite{T05, Mat05, KM06}, Fuglede's conjecture sparked many interesting results, and has been proved in many special cases, such as when $\Omega$ is a convex body \cite{LM22}.

One interesting area of research in spectrality is in product domains. If $E \subset \R^n$ and $F \subset \R^m$ are bounded sets of positive measure, then $E$ and $F$ being spectral in $\R^n$ and $\R^m$ implies that $\Omega = E \times F$ is spectral in $\R^n \times \R^m$, since the product of spectra for $E$ and $F$ forms a spectrum for $\Omega$ \cite[Thm.~3]{JP99}. Kolountzakis asked in \cite{K16} whether the converse is true, and this statement was formulated explicitly as a conjecture in \cite{GL20}:

\begin{conjecture}
    Let $E \subset \R^n, F \subset \R^m$ be bounded and measurable sets. Then $\Omega = E \times F$ is spectral if and only if $E$ is spectral in $\R^n$ and $F$ is spectral in $\R^m$.
\end{conjecture}

If some spectrum $\Lambda$ for $\Omega$ has a product structure, i.e. $\Lambda = U \times V$, then $U$ and $V$ can serve as spectra for the factors $E$ and $F$ \cite[Lemma~2]{JP99}, but in general we cannot assume that the spectrum $\Lambda$ has such a product structure. Nevertheless, there have been results in certain special cases.

In \cite{GL16}, Greenfeld and Lev proved that this conjecture holds when one of the factors, i.e. $E$, is an interval in $\R$. \cite{K16} proved that it holds when $E$ is the union of two intervals in $\R$. \cite{GL20} then proved the conjecture when $E$ is a convex polygon in $\R^2$. \cite{KLM} proved that if $\Omega = E \times F$ where $E$ is a convex body in $\R^n$ and $F$ is any bounded, measurable set in $\R^m$, then $\Omega = E \times F$ being spectral implies that $E$ must be spectral (but there is no claim on the spectrality of $F$). Recently, \cite{Som24} proved that the conjecture is false in general by constructing a counterexample, a set $\Omega = E \times F \subset \R^6$ such that $E \subset \R^3$ is not spectral.

In this paper, we focus on spectral product sets where one of the factors is a perturbation of an interval. This is inspired by \cite{KL02} which focuses on sets $E \subset \R$ contained in intervals of length strictly less than $3|E|/2$. Specifically, they prove the following:

\begin{theorem}
Suppose $E \subseteq [0,L]$ is measurable with measure 1 and $L = 3/2 - \epsilon$ for some $\epsilon > 0$. Let $\Lambda \subset \mathbb{R}$ be a discrete set containing 0. Then
\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(a)] if $E+\Lambda = \mathbb{R}$ is a tiling, it follows that $\Lambda = \mathbb{Z}$.
    \item[(b)] if $\Lambda$ is a spectrum of $E$, it follows that $\Lambda = \mathbb{Z}$.
\end{enumerate}
\label{thm_KL}
\end{theorem}

They note that this upper bound $L < 3/2$ is optimal since the set $[0,1/2) \cup [1,3/2]$ is contained in $[0,3/2]$, tiles $\mathbb{R}$ with translation set $\{0,1/2\} + 2\mathbb{Z}$, and has the spectrum $\{0,1/2\} + 2\mathbb{Z}$, so it has neither a lattice translation set nor a lattice spectrum.

Our main theorem is the following:

\begin{theorem}
Let $E$ be measurable with measure $1$ and $E\subset[0,3/2-\epsilon]$ for some $\epsilon > 0$, and let $F\subset \R^m$ be bounded and measurable with positive measure. If $E \times F$ is spectral, then both $E$ and $F$ are spectral.
\label{thm_main}
\end{theorem}

If $E\subset \R^d$ is measurable, then $\chi_E$ denotes the indicator function of $E$. For $f\in L^1(\R^d)$, we define its Fourier transform by
\begin{equation}
    \hat{f}(\xi)=\int_{\R^d} f(x)e^{-2\pi i\langle \xi,x\rangle}\dx, \qquad \xi\in \R^d.
\end{equation}

To show that $E$ is spectral, we use a ``weak tiling" condition, which was first applied to Fuglede's conjecture in \cite{LM22}. To show that $F$ is spectral, we use orthogonal packing regions to force many real zeros of $\hat{\chi_E}$, and then rule this out using a standard density-completeness estimate from the theory of nonharmonic Fourier series.

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Preliminaries and Results from the Literature}
We begin by collecting several definitions and results from the literature that will be used in the proof.

We first recall the notion of the essential difference set, following \cite[Definition~4.1]{KLM}.

\begin{ndefn}
If $E\subset \R^d$ is a bounded, measurable set, then its \emph{essential difference set} is
\begin{equation}
    \Delta(E)=\{t\in \R^d : m(E\cap(E+t))>0\}.
\end{equation}
\end{ndefn}

The set $\Delta(E)$ is open and origin-symmetric, in the sense that $-\Delta(E)=\Delta(E)$. If $E$ is open, then $\Delta(E)=E-E$.

The first result we need is the following lemma, proved in \cite{KL02}. This lemma is crucial for their proof of Theorem \ref{thm_KL}. Its proof is elementary and proceeds by considering the ranges $0<t\leq 1/2$, $1/2<t\leq 3/4$, and $3/4<t<1$.

\begin{lemma}[{\cite[Lemma~1]{KL02}}]
    Suppose that $E\subseteq[0,L]$ is measurable with measure $1$ and that $L=3/2-\epsilon$ for some $\epsilon>0$. Then $\Delta(E)$ contains the open interval $(-1,1)$.
\label{lem:overlap}
\end{lemma}

We next use the notion of an orthogonal packing region, following \cite[Section~3.6]{GL20}. This will be key for us to show that the second factor $F$ in $E \times F$ is spectral, after showing that $E$ is spectral. The normalized version of the result we need was proved by Kolountzakis in \cite[Thm.~2]{K16}. We will use the more general formulation given in \cite[Cor.~4.3]{GL20}.

\begin{ndefn}
If $E$ and $D$ are bounded, measurable sets in $\R^d$, then $D$ is called an
\emph{orthogonal packing region} for $E$ if $\hat{\chi_E}$ has no zeros in $\Delta(D)$.
If $D$ is open, then this is equivalent to saying that $\hat{\chi_E}$ has no zeros in $D-D$.
\end{ndefn}

\begin{theorem}[{\cite[Cor.~4.3]{GL20}; see also \cite[Thm.~2]{K16}}]
    Suppose that $\Omega=E\times F\subset \mathbb{R}^n\times \mathbb{R}^m$ is spectral. If $E$ admits an orthogonal packing region $D\subset \mathbb{R}^n$ with $m(D)=m(E)^{-1}$, then $F$ is spectral.
\label{thm:orthogonal-packing}
\end{theorem}

The next result is proved in \cite{LM22} and is an important tool in their proof of Fuglede's conjecture for convex bodies. They show that spectrality of $\Omega$ implies that $\Omega$ ``weakly tiles" its complement $\Omega^c$. This link between spectrality and a notion of tiling has been useful far beyond their original paper. The result below it is proved in \cite{KLM}. This result establishes that Conjecture 1.1 is true if the condition of spectrality is replaced by the weak tiling condition of \cite[Thm.~1.5]{LM22}. We will use both of these results in conjunction to show that $E$ and $F$ both weakly tile their complements, assuming that $E \times F$ is spectral.

\begin{ndefn}
We say that a bounded, measurable set $E\subset \R^d$ \emph{weakly tiles its complement}
$E^c=\R^d\smallsetminus E$ if there exists a positive, locally finite measure $\mu$ on
$\R^d$ such that $\chi_E\ast \mu=\chi_{E^c}$ almost everywhere. In this case, $\mu$ is called
a \emph{weak tiling measure} for $E$. If, in addition, $\mu$ is a sum of unit point masses,
then we call the weak tiling a \emph{proper tiling}.
\end{ndefn}

\begin{theorem}[{\cite[Thm.~1.5]{LM22}}]
    Let $\Omega$ be a bounded, measurable set in $\mathbb{R}^d$. If $\Omega$ is spectral, then its complement $\Omega^c=\mathbb{R}^d\smallsetminus\Omega$ admits a weak tiling by translates of $\Omega$.
\label{thm:spectral-weak}
\end{theorem}

\begin{theorem}[{\cite[Thm.~1.7]{KLM}}]
    Let $E\subset \mathbb{R}^n$ and $F\subset\mathbb{R}^m$ be two bounded, measurable sets. Then the product set $E\times F$ can weakly tile its complement in $\mathbb{R}^n\times\mathbb{R}^m$ by translations if and only if both $E$ and $F$ weakly tile their complements in $\mathbb{R}^n$ and $\mathbb{R}^m$, respectively.
\label{thm:product-weak}
\end{theorem}

We will also use the following support condition for weak tilings of complements.

\begin{lemma}[{\cite[Cor.~2.6]{LM22}}]
    Let $E$ be a bounded, measurable set in $\mathbb{R}^d$. Assume that for some positive and locally finite measure $\mu$ on $\mathbb{R}^d$, we have $\chi_E*\mu=\chi_{E^c}$ almost everywhere. Then $\supp(\mu)\subset\Delta(E)^\complement$.
\label{lem:support}
\end{lemma}

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Main Arguments}\label{s:main}

\subsection{Perturbation of interval admits lattice tiling}

For a measurable set $E\subset \R$, we write
\begin{align*}
\essinf E&:=\sup\{a\in \R: m(E\cap(-\infty,a))=0\},\\
\esssup E&:=\inf\{b\in \R: m(E\cap(b,\infty))=0\}.
\end{align*}

\begin{lemma}
Let $E\subset [a,b]$ be measurable, let $b-a\leq 2$, and suppose that $\Delta(E)\supset (-1,1)$. Then any weak tiling of $E^c$ by $E$ must be a proper tiling.
\label{lem:proper-tiling}
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
    Let $\mu$ be a weak tiling measure for $E$, so that $\chi_E*\mu=\chi_{E^c}$ almost everywhere. Replacing $a$ and $b$ by $\essinf E$ and $\esssup E$, respectively, does not increase $b-a$, and all subsequent inclusions involving $[a,b]$ are understood up to null sets. Thus we may assume that $a=\essinf E$ and $b=\esssup E$. By Lemma \ref{lem:support}, $\supp(\mu)\subset \Delta(E)^\complement$, and so
    $$\supp(\mu)\cap(-1,1)=\varnothing.$$

    We first note that $b-a\geq 1$. Indeed, if $b-a<1$, then $(b-1,a)\cup(b,a+1)$ is a set of positive measure contained in $E^c$. For any $x$ in this set, every translate $E+t$ which contains $x$ must have $t\in(-1,1)$, so $\chi_E*\mu$ vanishes almost everywhere on this set. This contradicts the weak tiling identity. Similarly, $E$ contains almost all points of $(b-1,a+1)$, if this interval is nonempty, since no point of $E^c\cap(b-1,a+1)$ can be covered by a translate $E+t$ with $t\in\supp(\mu)$.

    Let
    $$a+s=\essinf\left(E^c\cap[a+1,\infty)\right).$$
    Since $E$ is contained in $[a,b]$ up to a null set, this number is finite and $a+s\leq b$. Thus $1\leq s\leq b-a\leq 2$, and $E$ contains almost all points of $(a+1,a+s)$. We claim that $\supp(\mu)\cap[1,s)=\varnothing$. To see this, let $u\in[1,s)$. Since $a=\essinf E$, there is some $\eta>0$ such that $u+\eta<s$ and $m(E\cap(a,a+\eta))>0$. But then $E+u$ has positive measure in $(a+u,a+u+\eta)$, while $E$ contains almost all points of this interval. Thus $m(E\cap(E+u))>0$, so $u\in\Delta(E)$, and hence $u\notin\supp(\mu)$.

    We now show that $\mu\{s\}=1$. Suppose first that $\mu\{s\}<1$. Since $\mu$ is locally finite, there are $\delta,\gamma>0$ such that $\mu([s,s+\delta))<1-\gamma$. Let $\mu'$ be the restriction of $\mu$ to $[s,s+\delta)$. If $x\in(a+s,a+s+\delta)$ and $x\in E+t$ for some $t\in\supp(\mu)$, then $t\in[s,s+\delta)$. Indeed, $t$ cannot lie in $(-1,1)$ or in $[1,s)$ by the support gaps above. If $t\leq -1$, then $E+t\subset(-\infty,b-1]$, while $x>a+s\geq a+1\geq b-1$. If $t\geq s+\delta$, then $E+t\subset[a+s+\delta,\infty)$, while $x<a+s+\delta$. Hence
    $$\chi_E*\mu=\chi_E*\mu' \quad \text{a.e. on } (a+s,a+s+\delta).$$
    But $\chi_E*\mu'\leq \mu([s,s+\delta))<1-\gamma$, while $E^c\cap(a+s,a+s+\delta)$ has positive measure by the definition of $s$. Indeed, if this intersection had measure zero for some $\delta>0$, then $E$ would contain almost all points of $(a+1,a+s+\delta)$, contradicting the definition of $a+s$. This contradicts $\chi_E*\mu=\chi_{E^c}$ almost everywhere, and therefore $\mu\{s\}\geq 1$.

    Since $s\in\supp(\mu)$, Lemma \ref{lem:support} gives $s\notin\Delta(E)$, so $E$ and $E+s$ are disjoint up to a null set. For almost every $x\in E+s$, we therefore have $x\in E^c$, and the weak tiling identity gives $\chi_E*\mu(x)=1$. Since all contributions are nonnegative and the atom at $s$ contributes $\mu\{s\}\chi_E(x-s)=\mu\{s\}$, we have
    $$1=\chi_E*\mu(x)\geq \mu\{s\}.$$
    Thus $\mu\{s\}\leq 1$, and hence $\mu\{s\}=1$.

    Define a new measure by
    $$\mu_1=(\mu+\delta_0-\delta_s)*\delta_{-s}.$$
    Since $\mu\{s\}=1$, this is again a positive, locally finite measure. Moreover,
    $$\chi_E*\mu_1(x)=\chi_E*(\mu+\delta_0-\delta_s)(x+s)=\chi_{E^c}(x+s)+\chi_E(x+s)-\chi_E(x)=\chi_{E^c}(x)$$
    for almost every $x$. Thus $\mu_1$ is also a weak tiling measure for $E^c$ by $E$. Applying the argument above to $\mu_1$ shows that $\mu_1$ has a unit atom at $s$ and no mass in $(0,s)$. Translating back, $\mu$ has a unit atom at $2s$ and no mass in $(s,2s)$. Continuing in this way, $\mu$ has unit atoms at $s,2s,3s,\ldots$ and no mass in the intervals $(ks,(k+1)s)$ for $k=0,1,2,\ldots$. Hence $\mu$ is a sum of unit point masses on $[0,\infty)$.

    Finally, let $\widetilde E=-E$ and $\widetilde\mu(A)=\mu(-A)$. Then $\widetilde E$ satisfies the hypotheses of the lemma and $\widetilde\mu$ is a weak tiling measure for $\widetilde E^c$ by $\widetilde E$. Applying the positive-side argument to $\widetilde\mu$, we conclude that $\mu$ is also a sum of unit point masses on $(-\infty,0]$. Hence the weak tiling is proper.
\end{proof}

\begin{corollary}
Let $m(E)=1$, $E\subset[0,L]$, where $L=3/2-\epsilon$ for some $\epsilon>0$. If $E$ weakly tiles its complement, then $E+\mathbb{Z}$ tiles $\mathbb R$.
\label{cor:lattice-tiling}
\end{corollary}

\begin{proof}
    By Lemma \ref{lem:overlap}, $\Delta(E)$ contains $(-1,1)$. Since $L<2$, Lemma \ref{lem:proper-tiling} implies that any weak tiling of $E^c$ by $E$ is proper. If $\mu=\sum_{\lambda\in\Lambda'}\delta_\lambda$ is the corresponding weak tiling measure, then $0\notin\Lambda'$ by Lemma \ref{lem:support}, and
    $$\chi_E*(\delta_0+\mu)=\chi_E+\chi_{E^c}=1$$
    almost everywhere. Hence $E+\Lambda$ tiles $\mathbb R$, where $\Lambda=\Lambda'\cup\{0\}$. Since $\mu$ is locally finite, $\Lambda$ is discrete, and by Theorem \ref{thm_KL}, $\Lambda=\mathbb{Z}$.
\end{proof}

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\subsection{Spectrality of second factor in product}

\begin{lemma}
    Let $m(E)=1$, $E\subset[0,3/2-\epsilon]$, and suppose $E$ tiles $\mathbb R$ with respect to $\mathbb{Z}$. Then $\hat{\chi_E}(\xi)\neq 0$ whenever $-1/2\leq\xi\leq 1/2$.
\label{lem:no-small-zeros}
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
    Since $E$ tiles with respect to $\mathbb{Z}$ and $E\subset [0, 3/2-\epsilon]$, there is a set $G\subset [0,1/2-\epsilon]$ such that $\chi_E=\chi_{[0,1]}-\chi_G+\tau_1\chi_G$ a.e., where $\tau_hf(x):=f(x-h)$. Indeed, for almost every $x\in[0,1]$, exactly one of $x$ and $x+1$ lies in $E$, and no other integer translate can occur; taking $G=\{x\in[0,1/2-\epsilon]:x+1\in E\}$ gives the claimed identity. We may assume without loss of generality that $m(G)> 0$, for otherwise $\chi_E=\chi_{[0,1]}$ almost everywhere, and so the zeros of $\hat{\chi_E}$ are precisely the non-zero integers. The case $\xi=0$ is immediate, since $\hat{\chi_E}(0)=m(E)=1$. Thus we may assume that $0<|\xi|\leq 1/2$. Then
    $$\hat{\chi_E}(\xi)=(e^{-2\pi i\xi}-1)\left(\hat{\chi_G}(\xi)-\frac{1}{2\pi i\xi}\right).$$
    The roots of $e^{-2\pi i\xi}-1$ are precisely the integers. Since $0<|\xi|\leq 1/2$, this factor is nonzero. Also, $|2\pi x\xi|<\pi/2$ for all $x\in G$, since $G\subset [0,1/2-\epsilon]$. This means that $\cos(2\pi x\xi)>0$ on $G$, so

    $$\Re(\hat{\chi_G}(\xi))=\int_G\cos(2\pi x\xi)dx=\int_G\left|\cos(2\pi x\xi)\right|dx.$$
    Here $\Re(z)$ denotes the real part of a complex number $z$.
    Since $\cos(2\pi x\xi)>0$ on $G$ and $m(G)>0$, the last integral is strictly positive. Thus $\Re(\hat{\chi_G}(\xi))>0$, while $1/(2\pi i\xi)$ is purely imaginary. Therefore $\hat{\chi_G}(\xi)-1/(2\pi i\xi)\neq 0$, which is what we needed to show.
\end{proof}

\begin{lemma}
Let $f\in L^1(\mathbb R)$, $\supp(f)\subset[a,b]$, and let
$$\Lambda_+\subset\{\xi>0:\hat f(\xi)=0\}.$$
If
$$\liminf_{r\to+\infty}\frac{1}{r}\#(\Lambda_+\cap[0,r])>b-a,$$
then $f=0$ almost everywhere.
\label{lem:zero-density}
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
    This follows from Young's completeness theorem for complex exponentials \cite[Ch.~3, Sec.~1, Thm.~2]{Young2001}. If $\hat f$ is identically zero, then $f = 0$ almost everywhere so there is nothing to prove. Otherwise, since $f$ is compactly supported, $\hat f$ is an entire function and its real zeros are discrete, so we may enumerate the elements of $\Lambda_+$ increasingly as $\lambda_1<\lambda_2<\cdots$. The density assumption implies that
    $$\liminf_{n\to\infty}\frac{n}{\lambda_n}>b-a.$$

    Let $L=b-a$ and $c=(a+b)/2$. After the change of variables $u=2\pi(x-c)$, the interval $[a,b]$ becomes $[-\pi L,\pi L]$, and for every $n$,
    $$0=\hat f(\lambda_n)=\frac{e^{-2\pi i c\lambda_n}}{2\pi}\int_{-\pi L}^{\pi L}f\left(c+\frac{u}{2\pi}\right)e^{-i\lambda_n u}\,du.$$
    Since $\liminf n/\lambda_n>L$, Young's theorem and complex conjugation imply that $\{e^{-i\lambda_n u}\}_{n=1}^{\infty}$ is complete in $C[-\pi L,\pi L]$. Hence the absolutely continuous measure
    $$f\left(c+\frac{u}{2\pi}\right)\,du$$
    annihilates a dense subset of $C[-\pi L,\pi L]$, and therefore it is the zero measure. Thus $f=0$ almost everywhere.
\end{proof}

\begin{lemma}
    Let $m(E)=1$, $E\subset[0,L]$ where $L=3/2-\epsilon$ for some $\epsilon>0$, and suppose $E$ tiles $\mathbb{R}$ with respect to $\mathbb{Z}$. Then $E$ admits an orthogonal packing region $D\subset \mathbb{R}$ with $m(D)=1$.
\label{lem:packing-region}
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
    Suppose $E\subset[0,L]$, $m(E)=1$, and that $E$ tiles $\mathbb{R}$ with respect to $\mathbb{Z}$. For each $n=1,2,3,\ldots$, let
    $$D_n:=\left(0,\frac12\right)\cup\left(n-\frac12,n\right).$$
    Then $D_n$ is open and $m(D_n)=1$.

    Suppose for contradiction that $E$ admits no orthogonal packing region $D\subset \mathbb{R}$ with $m(D)=1$. In particular, no set $D_n$ is an orthogonal packing region for $E$. Since $D_n$ is open, we have $\Delta(D_n)=D_n-D_n$, and
    $$\Delta(D_n)=\left(-n,-n+1\right)\cup\left(-\frac12,\frac12\right)\cup(n-1,n).$$
    Because $D_n$ is not an orthogonal packing region for $E$, $\hat{\chi_E}$ has a zero in $\Delta(D_n)$. By Lemma \ref{lem:no-small-zeros}, $\hat{\chi_E}$ does not vanish on $\left(-\frac12,\frac12\right)$, so $\hat{\chi_E}$ has a zero either in $\left(-n,-n+1\right)$ or in $(n-1,n)$. Since $\chi_E$ is real-valued, the zero set of $\hat{\chi_E}$ is symmetric about the origin. Therefore for each $n=1,2,3,\ldots$ there is a zero $b_n\in(n-1,n)$ of $\hat{\chi_E}$, and then $-b_n$ is also a zero of $\hat{\chi_E}$.

    Since $E$ tiles $\mathbb{R}$ with respect to $\mathbb{Z}$, we have $\sum_{m\in\mathbb{Z}}\chi_E(x+m)=1$ for almost every $x\in\mathbb{R}$. Taking Fourier coefficients on $\mathbb{R}/\mathbb{Z}$, we obtain $\hat{\chi_E}(k)=0$ for every nonzero integer $k$.

    Let $\Lambda_+=\{\xi>0:\hat{\chi_E}(\xi)=0\}$. The zeros $b_n$ lie in disjoint intervals $(n-1,n)$, and none of them is an integer. If $r\in[N,N+1)$, then $\Lambda_+\cap[0,r]$ contains $1,\ldots,N$ and $b_1,\ldots,b_N$, so $\#(\Lambda_+\cap[0,r])\geq 2N$. Therefore
    $$\liminf_{r\to+\infty}\frac{1}{r}\#(\Lambda_+\cap[0,r])\geq 2.$$
    Since $\chi_E$ is supported in an interval of length $L=3/2-\epsilon<2$, Lemma \ref{lem:zero-density} implies that $\chi_E=0$ almost everywhere, contradicting $m(E)=1$.
\end{proof}

\section{Conclusion}\label{s:argument}
We now deduce Theorem 1.3 from the results we have already proved.

\noindent\emph{Proof of Theorem 1.3.}
    Let $m(E)=1$, $E\subset [0, 3/2-\epsilon]$, let $F\subset \R^m$ be bounded and measurable with positive measure, and let $E\times F$ be spectral. By Theorem \ref{thm:spectral-weak}, $E\times F$ weakly tiles its complement in $\mathbb R\times \mathbb R^m$. By Theorem \ref{thm:product-weak}, $E$ weakly tiles its complement in $\mathbb R$. Corollary \ref{cor:lattice-tiling} then shows that $E$ tiles $\mathbb R$ with respect to $\mathbb Z$. By the lattice case in Fuglede's original paper \cite{Fug74}, this implies that $\mathbb Z$ is a spectrum for $E$, and hence $E$ is spectral. By Lemma \ref{lem:packing-region}, $E$ admits an orthogonal packing region $D\subset \R$ with $m(D)=1=m(E)^{-1}$. Theorem \ref{thm:orthogonal-packing} therefore implies that $F$ is spectral. \qed

